Caldwell</strong>, a bit bleary-eyed along with the rest of the Washington =
media world (and members of Congress) after last night=E2=80=99s stemwinder=
 of a non=E2=80=93State of the Union speech. Before <strong>Trump </strong>=
took the mic, I joined NBC News=E2=80=99s <strong>Tom Llamas</strong>, who =
was just named as <strong>Lester Holt</strong>=E2=80=99s successor on <em>N=
ightly News</em>, and <strong>Hallie Jackson</strong> on set for their spec=
ial coverage. I=E2=80=99m going to spare you the highlights and hot takes=
=E2=80=94I=E2=80=99m sure you=E2=80=99ve
had enough of those already=E2=80=94except to say that whatever you think o=
f <strong>Trump</strong>, he is a master emcee.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I=
n tonight=E2=80=99s issue, I explore another type of performative politics=
=E2=80=94Republicans=E2=80=99 contradictory relationship with the president=
=2E Privately, of course, many lawmak=
ers are uneasy about the president=E2=80=
=99s trade wars with Canada and Mexico and China, and at least <em>somewhat=
</em> concerned
about the depth of <strong>Elon Musk</strong>=E2=80=99s cuts to government =
functions and services. Publicly, however, most are reciting the mantra tha=
t these are all just <em>temporary</em> dislocations on the eventual path t=
o economic nirvana. Along the way, Republicans are also ceding their own po=
wers to a president they can only hope is successful.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Still, =
there=E2=80=99s one Republican who has been remarkably consistent in
his critique that Congress has ceded far too much authority to the executiv=
e: <strong>Rand Paul</strong>. Our conversation about Washington=E2=80=99s =
crumbling division of power, below the fold.</p></div>
